As can be seen, the data set has noticeably more females than males. The mean age for both groups is ~20, although the male distribution is more wide due to a lesser number of young students. The female attitude distribution is flat from 2.5-3.5, whereas male attitude is skewed higher. Both groups favor deep learning approaches, and less so strategic and surface level approaches - although females had a more narrow distribution than males. The exam point distribution for both groups is nearly equal, with males having a small peak at higher scores.

Before looking at exam points, thereâs two noticeable correlations. Malesâ surface level learning and deep learning are significantly negatively correlated. A similar relationship is noticeable in malesâ surface level learning and attitude. For the whole sample, strategic learning is negatively correlated with surface level learning.

Finally, looking at the whole population, exam points are positively correlated with attitude and strategic learning (to a lesser extent) and negatively correlated with surface level learning.

3. Regression model

With the above mentioned three variables, we will make a regression model for exam points.

m <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014)
summary(m)

As such the model is okay. The residual median is near 0 and on average a prediction may deviate by 5 points As stated previously attitude and strategic learning have a positive correlation whereas surface learning has negative.Looking at each contributing variable only attitude has a statistically significant relationship with exam points with a p-value of 1.93e-08. Thus we will remove the other variables from the model.

4. Corrected model

m_corr <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
summary(m_corr)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09


Now the p-value of attitude is 4.12e-09, and overall the model is better without the over fitting. The intercept is 11.6 so on average if a student scored 0 in the attitude survey their exam score would be this value. The slope for attitude is 3.53, so if attitude increases by one predicted exam points increase by this value. The multiple R-squared value of the model is 0.191, therefore, attitude can explain 19.1 % of variance in exam points.

5. Diagnostic plots

Finally, we will investigate the validity of the model with a few diagnostic plots.

#par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(m_corr,which=(c(1,2,5)))


The assumed linear relationship between attitude and exam points holds true, since the residuals vs fitted line is straight. Although the data points are generally well distributed on the line variance seems to be higher at lower exam scores. Subjects 145, 56 and 35 were identified as outliers.

The Normal Q-Q plot shows that the residuals follow normal distribution well, although it is slightly skewed to higher values. The same outliers as before were noticed. Thus, the results of the statistical tests were valid.

The residuals vs leverage plot tells us which data points were most influential for the model fitting. Outliers 56 and 35 are visible again, but instead of 145 71 was noticed. However, as no data points are outside Cookâs distance there are no outliers that significantly influenced our model. Thus, the model is robust enough that its fitting wouldnât change a lot if some data points were removed.

The collected data includes several background factors such as the attended school, sex, age, family size etc. We will be looking at how high alcohol consumption relates to the other factors. Alcohol use is classified high when the mean value of weekday and weekend alcohol use is 2 on a scale of 1-5.

3. Hypothesis creation

The four variables of interest relating to high alcohol use Iâve chosen are number of school absences, weekly study time, quality of family relationships and current health status.

My hypotheses for these factors are the following: high alcohol use should -

  1. positively correlate with absences
  2. negatively correlate with weekly study time
  3. negatively correlate with family relationship quality
  4. negatively correlate with good health

4. Variable exploration

First letâs look at absences.

Using these variables, we will create a logistic regression model for alcohol consumption.

Absences, weekly study time and (less so) quality of family relationship are statistically significant and their relation to high alcohol use fits with our hypotheses. As we saw with health, its positively correlated instead of negatively correlated with high alcohol use, but it isnât statistically significant.

The non-significance of health on alcohol consumption can be seen in the confidence interval of health, as it includes 1. Thus we cannot say whether the true odds ratio is above or below 1, i.e.Â whether for the true population health has a positive or negative effect on the odds of high alcohol consumption. For each absence the OR indicates that it increases the odds of being a high consumption individual by 7 % (for true population 4-13 %) and for weekly study time each point (i.e.Â increase in category from <2 to 2-5 hours) decreases odds by 42.1 % (22-58 %) and for each point increase of family relationship quality the odds decrease by 24.2 % (2-41 %).

6. Predictive power

Weâll only take the significant variables and see how this model performs.

#make new model
new_m <- glm(high_use ~ absences + studytime + famrel, data = alc, family = "binomial")
#predict for each student whether they are high_use or not based on the variables
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = predict(new_m, type = "response"))
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

#cross tabulation
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction) %>% prop.table()
##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE
##    FALSE 0.65945946 0.04054054
##    TRUE  0.25405405 0.04594595
#optionally calculate training error with loss function
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2945946
#creating simple guessing strategy, randomly assign a number for each student within the range of student number
random_num <- sample(1:nrow(alc),nrow(alc))
alc <- mutate(alc, rand = random_num)
#count the number of high use students
num_high_use <- sum(alc$high_use) 
#if the random index is below the number of high use students predict them as a high use student
alc <- mutate(alc, naive_prediction = rand < num_high_use)
#this results in random guessing, but at least the proportion of high use students should be similar
print("True number of high use students:")
## [1] "True number of high use students:"
sum(alc$high_use)
## [1] 111
print("Randomly assigned number of high use students:")
## [1] "Randomly assigned number of high use students:"
sum(alc$naive_prediction)
## [1] 110
#finally, test its function with cross tabulation
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$naive_prediction) %>% prop.table()
##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE
##    FALSE 0.48378378 0.21621622
##    TRUE  0.21891892 0.08108108


The proportion of falsely assigned individuals is 0.254 + 0.041 = 0.295 -> 29.5 %. The same value is calculated with the loss function. Therefore, roughly every third guess is wrong.

With a completely random assignment, but still keeping the proportion of high alcohol consumption students correct gives a value of 0.232 + 0.235 = 0.467 -> 46.7 %. Much worse. Therefore, although the model has a large error, it is still better than randomly guessing based on the proportion of populations.

5. Linear discriminant analysis fitting

Next, weâll create a LDA model for predicting the categorical crime rate.

#creating the model
lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)
#arrows for visualization
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
#turning classes numeric for visualization
classes <- factor(train$crime) %>% unclass() %>% as.numeric()
plot(lda.fit,dimen=2,col = classes,pch=classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)


LDA was able to separate the high crime towns very well from the other towns using index of accessibility to radial highways. Similarly there is a clear gradient from low to med_high towns caused by nitrogen oxides concentration and proportion of residential land zoned for lots, in other words, areas like suburbs have less crime whereas urban areas have more. (Sidenote: I couldnât get pch to work in plot())

The data to be analyzed combines human welfare and gender equality data sets for countries. Hereâs explanations for the variables:

  • Life.Exp = life expectancy
  • Edu.Exp = expected years of schooling
  • GNI = gross national income per capita
  • Mat.Mor = maternal mortality ratio
  • Ado.Birth = adolescent birth rate
  • Parli.F = percentage of female representatives in parliament
  • Edu2.FM =ratio of female and male populations with secondary education
  • Labo.FM = ratio of female and male populations within the workforce


First, letâs look at obvious skews between mean and median. GNI, maternal mortality ratio and adolescent birth rate all have a higher mean value than median. Thus, although generally for countries the values are low, thereâs some countries with very high values which skew the results. This is verified in the pair plot distribution. Life expectancy and proportion of women in parliament are mirrored, where a clear peak is formed at the end or start respectively, but the drop off is gentle towards lower or higher values respectively.

Adolescent birth rate and maternal mortality ratio have nearly identical correlation profiles, and similarly proportion of women vs men in secondary education, life expectancy, expected years of schooling and GNI have very similar correlation profiles. These two variable groups correlate negatively with each other, which makes sense, as countries with good education and economy generally have better conditions and rights for women. Proportion of women vs men in the labour force or proportion of women in parliament only have weak correlations.

3. PCA with scaling

Letâs try scaling the variables first and then creating the plot

#standardize
human_std <- scale(human)

#pca 2
pca_std <- prcomp(human_std)
#make the percentages for principal components
s_std <- summary(pca_std)
pca_pr_std <- round(100*s_std$importance[2, ], digits = 1)
#prep the labels
pc_lab_std<- paste0(names(pca_pr_std), " (", pca_pr_std, "%)")
# draw the pca
biplot(pca_std, cex = c(0.7, 0.8), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab = pc_lab_std[1], ylab = pc_lab_std[2])


After scaling the data, a more rational PCA plot is made, where PC1 explains 53 % of variance and PC2 16 %. Countries are distributed along PC1 almost equally strongly towards negative values by expected years of education, life expectancy, gross national income and proportion of women vs men in secondary education. Their angles are similar as they all correlate together as noted before. Maternal mortality ratio and adolescent birth rate go hand in hand, and they pull countries to the positive values on PC1. PC2 on the other hand is described by proportion of women vs men in workforce and proportion of women in parliament, which are relatively closely correlated. This allows a more nuanced look at gender equality in countries without it being skewed by generally better healthcare.

Clearly standardization is essential for PCA, as GNI with its very high numeric values (max: 123124) completely overtakes the whole unscaled PCA plot. With rounding the principal component 1 explained 100 % of variation. Still, the plot did create a nice pattern, but its impossible to say what contributed to it, probably the second numerically highest variable which was maternal mortality ratio. As this is highly correlated with GNI, the plot is almost one dimensional. Scaling led to a very different plot, which was able to separate countries by variables with smaller numeric values.

4. PCA interpretation of standardized data

PC1 essentially describes the economic situation in countries, as a healthier economy leads to better healthcare and thus allows women to have better conditions and for them to also participate in the educational system. PC2 on the other hand gives a better look on the cultural position of women in these countries. Letâs look at the four quadrants separately.

When PC1 and PC2 are positive the economic situation is poor, but women have, at least relatively, a lot of power in both the workforce and politically. Taking the clear outlier Rwanda as an example, although it ranks averagely on PC1, it seems to rank highest in terms of gender equality. Indeed this is confirmed by the first paragraph in the wikipedia article on the gender equality in Rwanda (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gender_equality_in_Rwanda).

When PC1 is positive and PC2 is negative both the economic conditions and womenâs rights are poor. As countries with active conflicts, such as Yemen and Afghanistan are highlighted here this makes sense.

When PC1 and PC2 are negative the economic situation is good but womenâs rights are poor. Qatar is a good example of a country with a very high GNI due to a small number of ultra rich individuals, but as it is an Islamic state women donât have a lot of power.

When PC1 is negative and PC2 is positive western countries are separated, with northern European countries furthest from the pack. Here economy and womenâs rights are in a relatively good position.

1. Longitudinal data analysis with an assumption of independence between measurements

In the first part of this report we will investigate data which lists rat weight as a function of time under different nutritional plans.

1.1. Data loading and early investigation

First letâs load in the data and explore it.

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)

#read data
RATSL <- read.csv("data/ratsl.csv")

#check data was read correctly
glimpse(RATSL)
## Rows: 176
## Columns: 5

  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  xlab("Time (d)") + ylab("Standardized weight (g)")

#add standard error as column, but dont divide by sqrt sample size yet because sample sizes vary
RATSS <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(Group, Time) %>%
  summarise( mean = mean(Weight), se = sd(Weight)) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Group'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
#go over each row
for(i in 1:nrow(RATSS)) 
{       
  #if belongs to group 1
  if (RATSS[i,1] == 1)
  {
    #divide by sqrt 8, where 8 is the number of rats in group 1
    RATSS[i,4] <- RATSS[i,4] / sqrt(8)
  } 
  else 
  {
    #otherwise divide by sqrt 4 which is the number of rats in groups 2 and 3
    RATSS[i,4] <- RATSS[i,4] / sqrt(4)
  }
}


#plot summary graph
ggplot(RATSS, aes(x = Time, y = mean, linetype = Group, shape = Group)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point(size=3) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-se, ymax=mean+se, linetype="1"), width=0.3) +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.8,0.8)) +
  xlab("Time(d)") + 
  ylab("Mean(g) +/- standard error(g)") + 
  ggtitle("Weight change of rats under different diets") +
  theme(legend.position = "right")


We are interested in seeing whether different diets induced different weight change profiles on rats. Evaluating the first graph by eye gives the impression that group 2 had the most weight gain, then group 3 and lastly group 1. The standardized graph shows well how groups 2 and 3 had significantly higher starting weights, which also stayed high.

The summary graph tells the same story. Additionally the error bars show how the standard error is the highest in group 2, probably due to the one rat with a very high starting weight. However, in general it is hard to see if there is a difference so letâs change strategies.

1.2. Box plots

Based on previous graphs the weight change is quite stable, i.e.Â it doesnât fluctuate remarkably. Thus, as a naive approach we will make box plots on the weight change between days 1 and 64 on an absolute and relative scale. This will naturally ignore all the other dayâs data but as there arenât remarkable fluctuations it should give us a good idea on the cumulation.

#as done in exercises, assuming day 1 is baseline, creating a summary for days 8-64, but simply plotting this would lead to a comparison between starting weights, which isn't very useful. 
#RATSLS <- RATSL %>%
#  filter(Time > 2) %>%
#  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
#  summarise( mean=mean(Weight) ) %>%
#  ungroup()

#calculate relative and absolute change between days 1 and 64
baseline <- filter(RATSL,Time==1)
endpoint <- filter(RATSL,Time==64)
endpoint <- endpoint %>%
  mutate(delta_abs = Weight-baseline$Weight) %>%
  mutate(delta_rel = Weight/baseline$Weight)

#boxplot of absolute weight change
ggplot(endpoint, aes(x = Group, y = delta_abs)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "point", shape=23, size=4, fill = "white") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Absolute weight change between days 1 and 64 (g)")

#boxplot of relative weight change
ggplot(endpoint, aes(x = Group, y = delta_rel)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "point", shape=23, size=4, fill = "white") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Relative weight change between days 1 and 64 (g)")


Based on absolute weight change my previous assessment that most weight gain happens in group 2, then 3, then 1 is correct. Groups 2 and 3 also have more variance. However, relative weight change paints a different picture, where groups 1 and 3 are equal, and 2 barely higher (a difference of ~5 %-units). Like before, groups 2 and 3 have slightly more variance than group 1. In both plots there is one outlier (from different groups), but with such a small sample size it seems unwise to remove them. Especially since the plots of previous graphs were reasonable. This outlier causes slight skewing in the distribution in the absolute scale for group 2.

1.3. Anova

Finally, as we have 3 samples (and thus a two-sample t-test is unsuitable), weâll perform anova. This time letâs represent weight gain as the mean from days 8-64. For fun, letâs also do it for day 1 vs day 64.

RATSLS <- RATSL %>%
  filter(Time > 1) %>%
  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
  summarise( mean=mean(Weight) ) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Group'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
#add baseline back
RATSLS1 <- RATSLS %>%
  mutate(baseline = baseline$Weight)

#fit linear model for anova
fit <- lm(mean ~ baseline + Group, data = RATSLS1)
#compute anova
anova(fit)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: mean
##           Df Sum Sq Mean Sq   F value   Pr(>F)    
## baseline   1 253625  253625 1859.8201 1.57e-14 ***
## Group      2    879     439    3.2219  0.07586 .  
## Residuals 12   1636     136                       
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#day 1 vs 64 comparison for fun
endpoint <- endpoint %>%
  mutate(baseline = baseline$Weight)
fit2 <- lm(Weight ~ baseline + Group, data = endpoint)
anova(fit2)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: Weight
##           Df Sum Sq Mean Sq  F value    Pr(>F)    
## baseline   1 285981  285981 961.2875 7.966e-13 ***
## Group      2   2620    1310   4.4042   0.03678 *  
## Residuals 12   3570     297                       
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1


Anova tells us that, as expected, the baseline is very significant for explaining variance between the means, but the treatment group isnât (p=0.076). Thus, at least with this sample size we would have to say that there isnât a difference between the distributions in groups, i.e.Â the diets didnât have differences on weight gain outcomes.

By only comparing day 1 and day 64, then the group does become significant (p=0.037). Of course, this kind of p-hacking leaves a bad taste in my mouth. However, as I argued in the box plot interpretations, the weight accumulation was very stable between weeks, and thus only looking at the furthest end points is somewhat justified (more prone to errors as well). Naturally this result only tells us that one of the treatment groups is significantly different from the rest, but without proper post-hoc tests (which should have been planned before hand) we canât know which group is the significantly different one, although group 2 is the likely candidate.

A more robust way to measure this change would be to take the days 1-32 data average and compare it to 32-64 average, as now using day 1 vs average is dependent on day 1 fluctuations, and day 1 vs day 64 is dependent on both of their fluctuations.
